### Example 48: Bottleneck distance between two persistence diagrams

The bottleneck distance measures how different two diagrams are (minimum cost of matching features, allowing diagonal moves).

```scheme
(define pts1 (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 0 1)))
(define pts2 (list (list 0 0) (list 2 0) (list 0 2)))

(define filt1 (map (lambda (r) (topo/vietoris-rips pts1 r)) (list 0.5 1.0 1.5)))
(define filt2 (map (lambda (r) (topo/vietoris-rips pts2 r)) (list 0.5 1.0 1.5)))

(define pers1 (topo/persistence filt1))
(define pers2 (topo/persistence filt2))

(define bottleneck (topo/bottleneck pers1 pers2))
bottleneck
```

[VISUAL: Graphing calculator, array display mode, shows a single number, the bottleneck distance]

<!-- BUILD: run on interpreter; `topo/bottleneck` computes the metric; output is the distance -->

---

### Example 49: Persistence diagram for a circle of points

8 points uniformly spaced on a circle should have one persistent 1-dimensional feature (the loop).

