## Topic 5: Knot Theory — Tying, Analyzing, and Classifying Knots

### Opening: The Mathematics of Tangles

A knot is a closed curve in 3-dimensional space (imagine tying a loop of string and gluing the ends). Two knots are equivalent if one can be deformed into the other without cutting. Knot theory, founded in the late 19th century by Tait, Kirkman, and Little (who cataloged knots while studying the topology of vortex atoms), became a rich branch of topology in the 20th century.

**History:** Knot theory was revitalized in the 1920s by Alexander (Alexander polynomial) and again in the 1980s by Jones (Jones polynomial). Modern knot invariants (polynomials, homology theories) distinguish knots and have applications in DNA biology (knotted DNA strands), polymer chemistry, and quantum field theory (topological quantum computing).

**Uses:** Knot theory appears in molecular biology (enzyme action on DNA), physics (quantum entanglement, gauge theory), and chemistry (molecular knots, catenanes). Computationally, knot invariants classify and simplify knot diagrams. Knot diagrams are drawn as planar projections with crossing information.

**What we'll cover:** We'll create knot diagrams (specified by crossing data), compute knot invariants (writhe, crossing number, unknot detection), and explore the relationship between different representations. We'll tie trefoils, figure-eights, and more complex knots, and check if a knot is the unknot (topologically a circle).

---

### Example 56: Defining a knot by its crossings

A knot diagram is a planar projection with crossings. Each crossing has an over/under strand. The verb `topo/knot` builds a knot from crossing data.

```scheme
; Trefoil knot: 3 crossings, minimal non-trivial knot
; Crossings encoded as (strand1 strand2 over-strand)
; Simplified encoding: list of crossing descriptors
(define trefoil
  (topo/knot
    (list (list 1 2 1)  ; crossing 1: strand 1 over strand 2
          (list 2 3 2)  ; crossing 2: strand 2 over strand 3
          (list 3 1 3)))) ; crossing 3: strand 3 over strand 1

trefoil
```

[VISUAL: D3-over-canvas interactive: knot diagram, planar projection with arcs and crossings marked over/under]

<!-- BUILD: run on interpreter; `topo/knot` constructs a knot object from crossing list; output is the knot structure -->

---

### Example 57: Crossing number of a knot

The crossing number is the minimum number of crossings in any diagram of the knot. The trefoil has crossing number 3.

```scheme
(define trefoil-crossings (topo/crossing-number trefoil))
trefoil-crossings
```

[VISUAL: Graphing calculator, array display mode, shows the number `3`]

<!-- BUILD: run on interpreter; `topo/crossing-number` returns the minimal crossing count; output is 3 -->

---

### Example 58: Writhe of a knot diagram

Writhe is the signed sum of crossings (+1 for right-handed, −1 for left-handed). It's an invariant of the diagram, not the knot itself, but useful.

```scheme
(define trefoil-writhe (topo/writhe trefoil))
trefoil-writhe
```

[VISUAL: Graphing calculator, array display mode, shows an integer, e.g., `3` or `-3` depending on orientation]

<!-- BUILD: run on interpreter; `topo/writhe` computes signed crossing sum; output is the writhe -->

---

### Example 59: Checking if a knot is the unknot

The unknot is a simple loop (topologically a circle). The verb `topo/unknot?` applies algorithms (Reidemeister moves, etc.) to check.

```scheme
; A trivial loop (unknot)
(define unknot (topo/knot (list)))  ; no crossings

(topo/unknot? unknot)
```

[VISUAL: Graphing calculator, array display mode, shows the boolean `#t`]

<!-- BUILD: run on interpreter; a knot with no crossings is the unknot; output is #t -->

